{"id":"astro-ph/0506450","submitter":"Gordon Ogilvie","authors":"Gordon I. Ogilvie","title":"Wave attractors and the asymptotic dissipation rate of tidal\n  disturbances","comments":"26 pages, 5 figures, to be published in J. Fluid Mech","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/S0022112005006580","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Linear waves in bounded inviscid fluids do not generally form normal modes\nwith regular eigenfunctions. Examples are provided by inertial waves in a\nrotating fluid contained in a spherical annulus, and internal gravity waves in\na stratified fluid contained in a tank with a non-rectangular cross-section.\nFor wave frequencies in the ranges of interest, the inviscid linearized\nequations are spatially hyperbolic and their characteristic rays are typically\nfocused on to wave attractors. When these systems experience periodic forcing,\nfor example of tidal origin, the response of the fluid can become localized in\nthe neighbourhood of a wave attractor. In this paper I define a prototypical\nproblem of this form and construct analytically the long-term response to a\nperiodic body force in the asymptotic limit of small viscosity. The vorticity\nof the fluid is localized in a detached shear layer close to the wave attractor\nin such a way that the total rate of dissipation of energy is asymptotically\nindependent of the viscosity. I further demonstrate that the same asymptotic\ndissipation rate is obtained if a non-viscous damping force is substituted for\nthe Navier-Stokes viscosity. I discuss the application of these results to the\nproblem of tidal forcing in giant planets and stars, where the excitation and\ndissipation of inertial waves may make a dominant, or at least important,\ncontribution to the orbital and spin evolution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Jun 2005 11:22:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-08-30"}
